com:
Post some classic British teatime treats.
There's nothing more welcoming than coming home from the tractor factory set in the cold and after a multiple mile walk.
Whether you like it or not - the British have adapted their cuisine to perfectly accentuate the climate that they live in.

As rain and darkness lashes upon their skin, the warmest and most wholesome foodstuffs warm the hearth within their heart.

The light draws dim and feeble - why haven't you tried a cuisine that was made for a dark and oppressing winter?

com:
What are some easy Christmas month cocktails to make?

I was at jewel and bought some wine that promised to be deep with spicy notes and nutty, so basically, dry, which is what I was looking for. I wasn't disappointed because it wasn't sweet at all and generally tasted nice, but even though i tried swirling it around in my mouth like they do on TV i couldn't make out "notes" of anything, not the blueberry or any of the stuff on the very descritptive label. It tasted "dry" and good to me.

I also bought a bottle of eggnog that suggested I buy a big plastic candy cane full of Fireball Whiskey single shots inside it on the label and that I do two shots of Fireball to one serving of eggnog. I'm drinking that right now and it's pretty good and pretty Christmasy. Tastes like eggnog with a hint of cinnamon.

I took a bit to find some stuff to drink this month. Anyone else trying to theme it up, or have cocktails to share?

You could try taking a scotch based old fashioned and then twisting it into a christmas version. If you don't have any bitters at hand, you could just make rich syrups (2 to 1 ratio of spice+sugar and water) and use those sparingly to avoid making it too sweet. Ground cinnamon cinnamon can also do a lot of work in order to make it feel more festive. Really just sprinkling ground cinnamon ontop of most scotch based cocktails does wonders in terms of making it feel "wintery". Creamy drinks + cinnamon is what I'd usually gravitate towards when making stuff for christmas.
I've been experimenting with amaretto/noyaux + frangelico mixed with various base spirits and bitters, currently enjoying a heavily modified godfather (1 part scotch, 1/2 part amaretto, 1/2 part frangelico, cinnamon bitters), it's pretty good and not too sweet.
Also can't forget the hot toddy, hot cocktails in general are excellent choices for winter.', 'time': 1670759792, 'resto': 18682980}]

i've also only had green. make cardamom icecream just don't use too much or it will taste soapy', 'time': 1670707847, 'resto': 18680997}, {'no': 18681016, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)16:31:01', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>18680997
Black cardamom is completely different, and super underrated. It's smoky, intensely camphor and piney. It's great with rich stews and curries, but I've fried a few pods with the beef and onions for chili and it was awesome.
Green cardamom is good for more than just scandinavian desserts and arabic coffee. They use it a bunch in middle eastern spice mixes for meats. I love using it along with cumin, coriander, chili powder, grated onion-garlic-ginger in a yogurt marinated lamb or chicken. It really gets those authentic Mecca vibes going.', 'time': 1670707861, 'resto': 18680997}, {'no': 18681041, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)16:36:33', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'Black cardamom is tricky to use. It has a strong taste and odour of camphor. If you're American and have very elderly relatives, you'll know camphor as the smell of mothballs.
I only know of Cambodians to use it with any regularity and even they don't use it all that much, either.
As for green, it's great in sweets and certain curries. I use it in my masala for tea along with cinnamon, peppercorn, nutmeg, cloves and a small bit of ginger.', 'time': 1670708193, 'resto': 18680997}, {'no': 18682559, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)23:28:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>18680997
black cardamom is used a lot in nepalese cooking. its generally used as spice for tempering other dishes. my personal favourite use for it is for making tempered rice. for some examples, google Taste of Nepal by Jyoti Pathak', 'time': 1670732911, 'resto': 18680997}]
